<p>
  Use the <code>aria-current</code> attribute to highlight the current page in a navigation, both visually and semantically.
</p>

{% highlight "html" %}
<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/about-us" aria-current="page">About us</a></li>
    <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>
{% endhighlight %}

<!-- teaser -->

<p>
  If you use a class like <code>.active</code> to highlight the current page within a set of links, only sighted users will be hinted at which page is the current page.
</p>

{% highlight "html" %}
<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/about-us" class="active">About us</a></li>
    <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>
{% endhighlight %}

{% highlight "css" %}
.active {
  font-weight: bold;
}
{% endhighlight %}

<p>
  Instead of a simple class, you can use the <code>aria-current</code> attribute with the <code>page</code> value. The attribute communicates the active page to assistive technology and you can use it to select the link in CSS.
</p>

{% highlight "html" %}
<nav>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/home">Home</a></li>
    <li><a href="/about-us" aria-current="page">About us</a></li>
    <li><a href="/contact">Contact</a></li>
  </ul>
</nav>
{% endhighlight %}

{% highlight "css" %}
[aria-current="page"] {
  font-weight: bold;
}
{% endhighlight %}

